# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lee-richmond
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lee-richmond/1879-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1879 throughout the world.
[src:lee-richmond/1879-in-baseball] Inter-league playoff: Providence Grays (NL) defeat Albany Blues (NA), 2 games to 0.
[src:lee-richmond/1880-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1880 throughout the world.
[src:lee-richmond/1882-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1882 throughout the world.
[src:lee-richmond/1883-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1883 throughout the world.
[src:lee-richmond/1886-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1886 throughout the world.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] On October 2, 1908, Addie Joss pitched a perfect game, the fourth in Major League Baseball (MLB) history, the second in American League history, and the second since the beginning of the modern era (1900).
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] He threw it at League Park, in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] Joss's three strikeouts are the fewest recorded in a modern era perfect game and the second-fewest in a perfect game in MLB history, trailing only the two strikeouts recorded by John Montgomery Ward in his 1880 perfect game.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] The Detroit Tigers, Chicago White Sox, and Joss's Cleveland Naps were engaged in a race for the post-season at the time of the game, with the Tigers seeking their second straight pennant, the White Sox trying to win their second in three years, and the Naps looking for their first.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] Three games remained in the regular season and the Naps were a half-game behind the Detroit Tigers as they headed into a match-up against the Chicago White Sox, who trailed the Naps by one game.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] Game attendance was announced at 10,598.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] The Naps faced future Hall of Fame pitcher Ed Walsh and recorded four hits; they were struck out by Walsh 15 times.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] The Naps' Joe Birmingham scored the team's only run, which came in the third inning.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] In the ninth inning, Joss retired the first two batters, then faced pinch hitter John Anderson.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] Anderson hit a line drive that would have resulted in a double had it not gone foul.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] He then hit a ball to Naps third baseman Bill Bradley which Bradley bobbled before throwing to first baseman George Stovall.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] Stovall dug the ball out of the ground to preserve the Naps' 1–0 lead.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] Joss's catcher in the game was the much traveled Jay Clarke.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] With the win, Joss recorded a perfect game, the second in American League history.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] He accomplished the feat with just 74 pitches, the lowest known pitch count ever achieved in a perfect game.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] The perfect game was the first of two no-hitters Joss pitched during his career.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] He no-hit the White Sox a second time on April 20, 1910, also by a 1–0 score.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss-perfect-game] He was the only pitcher to throw two no-hitters against the same team until San Francisco Giant Tim Lincecum no-hit the San Diego Padres on July 13, 2013, and June 25, 2014.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss was born and raised in Wisconsin, where he attended St.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Mary's College (later part of Wyalusing Academy) in Prairie du Chien and the University of Wisconsin.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Mary's and then played in a semipro league where he caught the attention of Connie Mack.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss did not sign with Mack's team, but he attracted further major league interest after winning 19 games in 1900 for the Toledo Mud Hens.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss had another strong season for Toledo in 1901.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] After an offseason contract dispute between Joss, Toledo and Cleveland, he debuted with the Cleveland club in April 1902.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss led the league in shutouts that year.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] By 1905, Joss had completed the first of his four consecutive 20-win seasons.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Off the field, Joss worked as a newspaper sportswriter from 1906 until his death.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In 1908, he pitched a perfect game during a tight pennant race that saw Cleveland finish a half-game out of first place; it was the closest that Joss came to a World Series berth.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The 1910 season was his last, and Joss missed most of the year due to injury.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In April 1911, Joss became ill and he died the same month due to tuberculous meningitis.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He finished his career with 160 wins, 234 complete games, 45 shutouts and 920 strikeouts.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Addie Joss was born on April 12, 1880, in Woodland, Dodge County, Wisconsin.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] His parents Jacob and Theresa (née Staudenmeyer) were farmers; his father, a cheesemaker who was involved in local politics, had emigrated from Switzerland.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] A heavy drinker of alcohol, he died from liver complications in 1890, when Joss was 10 years old; Joss remained sober throughout his life as a result of his father's death.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss attended elementary school in Juneau and Portage and high school at Wayland Academy in Beaver Dam, Wisconsin.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] By age 16 he finished high school and began teaching himself.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He was offered a scholarship to attend St.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Mary's College (also known as Sacred Heart College) in Watertown, where he played on the school's baseball team.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He also attended the University of Wisconsin (now University of Wisconsin–Madison), where he studied engineering.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Officials in Watertown were impressed with the quality of play of St.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Mary's and put the team on a semipro circuit.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] During his time on the semipro circuit, Joss employed his unique pitching windup, which involved hiding the ball until the very last moment in his delivery.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Connie Mack also sent a scout to watch Joss and later offered the young pitcher a job playing on his Albany club in the Western League, which Joss declined.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In 1899, Joss played for a team in Oshkosh, earning $10 per week ($387 in today's dollars).
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] After player salaries were frozen by team owners, Joss joined the junior team in Manitowoc, which had been split into two teams, as a second baseman and was soon promoted to the senior squad, where he was developed into a pitcher.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He was seen by a scout for the Toledo Mud Hens and in 1900 accepted a position with the team for $75 per month ($2,903).
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] While in Ohio he was considered "the best amateur pitcher in the state." He started the Mud Hens' season opener on April 28 and earned the win in the team's 16–8 victory.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Midway through the 1901 season, the Boston Americans of the upstart American League offered $1,500 ($58,050) to Toledo to buy out Joss's contract.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Louis Cardinals of the National League (NL) matched Boston's offer; Toledo rejected both offers.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss continued to pitch for the Mud Hens and by the end of the 1901 season he had won 27 games and had 216 strikeouts (some sources say 25 games).
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] After the season ended, Joss returned to Wisconsin where he led Racine to the 1901 Wisconsin baseball state championship against Rube Waddell's Kenosha squad.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He also enrolled at Beloit College and played American football.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] It was reported that Joss had signed with the Brooklyn Dodgers of the National League as early as August 18 and received a $400 advance ($15,480), but Joss denied receiving any money.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Mud Hens owner Charles Stroebel stated that he had signed Joss and other Mud Hens players for the 1902 season on August 12 and that the Western League was under the protection of the National League through September 1901.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Before 1901 ended, the Cleveland Bronchos offered $500 ($19,350) to Toledo in exchange for Joss and manager Bob Gilks, who would be a scout for Cleveland.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Toledo and Joss agreed and Joss was now a member of the American League, which was paying a premium on baseball talent to rival the National League.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Dodgers owner Charles Ebbets invited Joss for a meeting, which Joss declined, and Joss let it be known that he had told Stroebel he would play for the Mud Hens for the 1902 season, and received a $150 ($5,582) advance in February 1902.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In March 1902, Joss signed with Cleveland.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] For not returning the entire advance, Joss was charged with a felony and Stroebel pursued legal action.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss made his major league debut with the Bronchos on April 26, and two days later he arrived in Toledo to turn himself in, accompanied by Bronchos majority owner Charles Somers, who was also American League vice president.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Stroebel also filed a civil suit against the Bronchos, stating that his business had been interfered with, but Stroebel agreed to withdraw his charges in July when he accepted Bronchos pitcher Jack Lundbom.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss made his major league debut with the Cleveland Bronchos (also known as the Bluebirds) against the St.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The Browns' Jesse Burkett hit a shallow pop fly in the direction of right fielder Zaza Harvey.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Home plate umpire Bob Caruthers ruled that Harvey did not make a clean catch, so Burkett was credited with a hit.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] (Harvey and witnesses said the ball never hit the ground.) Joss finished his major league debut with a one-hitter.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss compiled a 17–13 record and 2.77 ERA during his major league rookie season.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He led the American League with five shutouts.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] On October 11, 1902, Joss married Lillian Shinivar in Monroe, Michigan.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Shinivar was in attendance when Joss made his professional debut with the Mud Hens in 1900.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The couple had a son, Norman, and a daughter, Ruth.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Following the conclusion of the 1902 season, Joss was selected to the All-Americans, an all-star team from the American League who played exhibition games against their counterparts from the National League.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] To begin the 1903 season, the Cleveland organization changed the team's name to the "Naps" in honor of second baseman Nap Lajoie.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In Joss' second year, he went 18–13 and lowered his ERA from the season before to 2.19.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] His walks plus hits per inning pitched (WHIP) was an MLB-low 0.948.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] For the 1904 season, the 24-year-old Joss went 14–10 with a 1.59 ERA and did not give up a home run during the season.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Illness during the season reduced his starts.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He had his first of four 20-win seasons in 1905 as he ended the season with a 20–12 record and 2.01 ERA.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He finished with a career-high 132 strikeouts.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In 1906 his 1.72 ERA was third in the league and he finished with a 21–9 record and tied a career-high with nine shutouts.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] To begin the 1907 season, Joss won his first 10 starts.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He threw two one-hitters during the season, the first on September 4 against the Detroit Tigers and the second on September 25 versus the New York Highlanders.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] When teammate Heinie Berger threw his own one-hitter on September 26, it marked just the second time since 1900 that two pitchers from the same team had thrown back-to-back one-hitters.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss finished the season with career-bests in wins (finished 27–11) and 338+2⁄3 innings pitched.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] His win total tied with Doc White for highest in the American League and his WHIP was second-best (behind Cy Young) while both his complete game (34) and shutout (6) totals were third-best in the league.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Before the 1908 season started, the Naps' home field, League Park, was expanded by about 4,000 seats.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In what proved to be one of the tightest ever pitching duels in a perfect game, Joss took the mound for the Naps, while the White Sox pitcher was future Hall of Famer Ed Walsh.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Neither pitcher would give up an earned run in the 1–0 game.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Walsh, blistering through his own 39 win season, struck out 15 batters, gave up only one base on balls and allowed only four scattered hits by the Naps.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The Naps' Joe Birmingham scored the team's only run, which came in the third inning—the lone, unearned run scored as a result of a botched pickoff play and a wild pitch.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The tension in the ballpark was described by one writer as "a mouse working his way along the grandstand floor would have sounded like a shovel scraping over concrete." Joss, having faced the minimum 24 batters in the first eight innings, retired the first two batters in the top of the ninth.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss then faced White Sox pinch hitter John Anderson.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Anderson hit a line drive that could have resulted in a double had it not gone foul.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He then hit a ball to Naps third baseman Bill Bradley, which Bradley bobbled before throwing to first baseman George Stovall.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Stovall dug the ball out of the dirt to achieve the final out.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] With the win, Joss recorded the second ever perfect game in MLB's modern era.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] After the game, Joss said, "I never could have done it without Larry Lajoie's and Stovall's fielding and without Birmingham's base running.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] For the season, Joss averaged 0.83 walks per nine innings, becoming one of 29 pitchers in MLB history to average less than one walk per nine innings.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] His season-ending WHIP of .806 is the fifth-lowest single-season mark in MLB history.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The Naps finished with a 90–64 record, a half-game behind Detroit.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] It was the closest Joss ever got to a World Series appearance.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] After amassing four consecutive 20-win seasons, Joss struggled in 1909 as a result of fatigue; by September he was shut down for the season.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss finished the year with a 14–13 record in 242+2⁄3 innings pitched and recorded a 1.71 ERA.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He finished fourth in the American League in ERA and third in WHIP (.944).
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss pitched a second no-hitter, on April 20, 1910, against the White Sox, becoming the first pitcher in MLB history to no-hit the same team twice, a feat not matched until Tim Lincecum of the San Francisco Giants no-hit the San Diego Padres in both 2013 and 2014.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In the second inning, the White Sox' Freddy Parent hit a ball toward third base.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Bill Bradley failed to field the ball cleanly and thus his throw to first base was not in time to get Parent out.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The initial ruling on the field was a base hit but it was later changed to an error.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss gave up two walks and recorded 10 assists.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He made just 13 appearances that season due to a torn ligament in his right elbow.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss made his last appearance of the season on July 25, and left the game in the fifth inning due to arm soreness.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In his final game, he allowed three runs on five hits and two walks with six strikeouts in a 4–0 loss.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In his final major league season, Joss finished with a 5–5 record in 107+1⁄3 innings.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] This marked the fifth time in Joss' nine years that the franchise finished with a losing record.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Of Joss' 160 major league wins, 45 were shutouts.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss' 1.89 career ERA is ranked second all-time (to Ed Walsh), while his 0.97 WHIP (walks and hits per inning pitched) is the lowest career WHIP in MLB history.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He finished with a 160–97 record, 234 complete games, and 920 strikeouts.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss' repertoire included a fastball, a "slow ball" (today known as a changeup), and an "extremely effective" curve.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Baseball historians Rob Neyer and Bill James ranked Joss' fastball third (1900–1904) and sixth (1905–1909) in the major leagues.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] George Moriarty explained that Joss had only one curveball because "he believed that with a few well mastered deliveries he could acquire great control and success with less strain on his arm." In an era filled with spitball pitchers, Joss achieved his success without ever altering the baseball.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Illness and injury accompanied Joss throughout much of his professional career.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In 1903, a high fever forced him to miss the last month of the season.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He contracted malaria in April 1904 and then missed several starts with a back injury in 1905.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss was concerned about supporting his family after his baseball career ended; many players of the day had little education and few marketable job skills beyond their abilities on the diamond.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] As sportswriter Franklin Lewis wrote, "Only a handful of players in the rough, stirring, early days of the major leagues arrived from campuses.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] And when they did, sometimes the shock was too great for them.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Some grizzled holdovers from the 1890s were around and they bore down heavily on the eardrums of the so-called college-boy set." Joss was hired as a sports columnist after the 1906 season for the *Toledo News-Bee*.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He also served as their Sunday sports editor.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] His writings proved so popular that sales of the paper increased and a special phone line was installed in his office to field the large volume of calls he received from fans.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The increased popularity gave him an advantage when negotiating with the Naps before the 1907 season, and the club agreed to pay him $4,000 (equivalent to $138,000 in 2025).
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He later also wrote for the *Cleveland Press* and covered the World Series for the *News-Bee* and *Press* from 1907 to 1909.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The *Press* introduced Joss in columns this way: "Of all the baseball players in the land, Addie Joss is far and away the best qualified for this work.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] During the 1908–1909 offseasons, Joss worked on designing an electric scoreboard that would later be known as the Joss Indicator.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The Naps decided to install the scoreboard, which allowed spectators to monitor balls and strikes at League Park.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss attended spring training with Cleveland before the start of the 1911 season.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He collapsed on the field from heat prostration on April 3 in an exhibition game in Chattanooga, Tennessee.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He was taken to a local hospital and released the next day.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] As early as April 7, press reports had taken note of his ill health, but speculated about "ptomaine poisoning" or "nervous indigestion." The Naps traveled to Toledo for exhibition games on April 10 and Joss went to his home on Fulton Street where he was seen by his personal physician, Dr.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Chapman thought Joss could be suffering from nervous indigestion or food poisoning.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] By April 9, as Joss was coughing more and had a severe headache, Chapman changed his diagnosis to pleurisy and reported that Joss would not be able to play for one month and would need ten days of rest to recover.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss could not stand on his own and his speech was slurred.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss was well-liked by his peers and baseball fans.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Upon hearing of his death, the *Press* wrote "every train brings flowers" and "floral tributes by the wagonload are hourly arriving at the Joss home from all sections of the country." His family arranged for the funeral to take place on April 17.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] On that day, the Naps were to face the Detroit Tigers.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Naps players signed a petition stating that they would not attend the game so they could instead attend the funeral.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] They asked for the game to be rescheduled, but the Tigers balked at the request.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] American League president Ban Johnson initially supported the Tigers' position, but he ultimately sided with the Naps.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Naps owner Charles Somers and 15 Naps players attended the funeral, which was officiated by player-turned-evangelist Billy Sunday.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The first "all-star" game was played as a benefit for Joss's family on July 24, 1911.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The Naps invited players from the other seven American League teams to play against them.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Visiting club players who were involved in the game included Home Run Baker, Ty Cobb, Eddie Collins, Sam Crawford, Walter Johnson, Tris Speaker, Gabby Street, and Smoky Joe Wood.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] "I'll do anything they want for Addie Joss' family", Johnson said.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Washington Senators manager Jimmy McAleer volunteered to manage the all-stars.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] "The memory of Addie Joss is sacred to everyone with whom he ever came in contact.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The man never wore a uniform who was a greater credit to the sport than he", McAleer said.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] The game was attended by approximately 15,270 fans and raised nearly $13,000 ($449,000 today) to help Joss' family members pay remaining medical bills.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] In 1981, Lawrence Ritter and Donald Honig included him in their book *The 100 Greatest Baseball Players of All Time.* They described what they called "the Smoky Joe Wood Syndrome", where a player of truly exceptional talent has a career curtailed by injury or illness.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] They argued that such a player should still be included among the greatest all-time players, in spite of career statistics that would not quantitatively rank him with the all-time greats.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] They believed that Joss' career ERA was proof enough of his greatness to be included.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] Joss was inducted into the Cleveland Guardians Hall of Fame on July 29, 2006.
[src:lee-richmond/addie-joss] He was inducted in the same class as Ray Chapman, Rocky Colavito, Al López, Sam McDowell, Al Rosen and Herb Score.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Lee Richmond was born on May 5, 1857, in Sheffield, Ohio, to Cyrus R.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Richmond and Eliza Richmond (née Tinan).
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He was the son and grandson of Baptist ministers, and was the youngest of nine children.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Richmond was raised in a farming community in Geneva, Ohio, and in 1873 attended a college preparatory academy affiliated with Oberlin College.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] It was here where Richmond first played baseball, alongside his brother Willis.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] For three years, Richmond pitched for both Oberlin's preparatory academy club and the school's college club.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] In 1876 he enrolled at Brown University, where he not only was elected class president, but also became a multisport athlete.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He was a pitcher and outfielder for the school's baseball team, and played in Brown's first intercollegiate football games.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] On June 2, 1879, Richmond was paid $10 ($346 in current dollar terms) to pitch for Worcester of the National Baseball Association in an exhibition game against the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He pitched a seven-inning no-hitter and signed with Worcester after the game.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] On July 28, he pitched a no-hitter against Springfield.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Worcester joined the National League in 1880, and Richmond signed with the team for $2,400 ($80,069 in current dollar terms) that season.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Before a game against Cleveland on June 12, Richmond was up all night taking part in college graduation events, and he went to bed at 6:30 AM.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He caught the 11:30 AM train for Worcester so he could pitch in the afternoon contest and then pitched a perfect game to beat Cleveland, 1–0.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] According to the *Chicago Tribune*, "The Clevelands were utterly helpless before Richmond's puzzling curves, retiring in every inning in one, two, three order, without a base hit.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] The Worcesters played a perfect fielding game." Cleveland pitcher Jim McCormick allowed three hits, and the only run was scored on a double error by second baseman Fred Dunlap.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Richmond graduated from Brown University four days after the perfect game, and he finished the year with a win–loss record of 32–32, a 2.15 earned run average, and 243 strikeouts in 590.2 innings pitched.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He was the first left-handed pitcher to win 30 games in a season.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Richmond found success throwing an offspeed pitch that he termed a "half-stride ball" and that other players referred to as a "drop ball".
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He also had a rising fastball that he called a "jump ball".
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He also learned to throw a curveball in college, even though a Brown physics professor tried to convince him that nothing could make a ball curve in midair.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] In both 1881 and 1882, Richmond pitched over 400 innings.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] After the 1882 season, the Worcester franchise disbanded, and Richmond played for the National League's Providence Grays in 1883.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He experienced arm problems and was primarily an outfielder that year.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He finished his MLB career with a record of 75–100, a 3.06 ERA, and 552 strikeouts.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Throughout his baseball career, Richmond dedicated a sizable portion of his time to his medical studies.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] As baseball historian John Richmond Husman notes, "[...] baseball was the means to his end.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He used it to finance his education." Four days after his perfect game, he graduated from Brown University with a Bachelor of Arts degree, and during the offseason for the next three years, continued his studies at the College of Physicians and Surgeons and University of the City of New-York.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] In 1883, he was awarded a Master of Arts from Brown and a medical degree from the University of the City of New-York.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] This made Richmond the first physician to play in a baseball league recognized by Major League Baseball.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] After his retirement from baseball following the 1883 season, Richmond worked with his tutor Dr.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Gardner in Providence, before returning to his home state of Ohio to set up a private practice facility in Conneaut.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] In 1886, Richmond attempted a brief, unsuccessful comeback with the Cincinnati Red Stockings of the American Association.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He lost two of the three games he pitched in, and allowed 16 earned runs in 18 innings.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Richmond then changed careers, and from 1890 to 1921, he was a high school chemistry teacher at Scott High School in Toledo, Ohio.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] Richmond married Mary Naomi Chapin, his former student, in 1892, and had three children: Ruth, Dorothy, and Jane.
[src:lee-richmond/lee-richmond] He died on October 1, 1929, at the age of 72.
